Introduction¶

Made by: Keilani Li¶

Hello! The goal of my project is to identify characteristics or behavioral patterns of people experiencing mental health issues. To reach my goal, I plan to analyze features from a mental health dataset from Kaggle and train a clustering model. Some of these features include signs of stress, mood swings, changes in habit, and other factors. I decided to use a clustering model since it's more appropriate for my goal and also because I wanted to practice it more.

I decided to choose this topic to promote mental health awareness. If we are able to figure out the behavioral patterns of people going through mental health struggles, it may encourage them to seek professional help to address those issues. Better yet, if we could recognize these signs of struggle in the people around us, we could offer them supportive resources since we know that they're going through something.

Background¶

As mentioned before, the dataset we'll be looking at is from Kaggle.com and it can be viewed or downloaded by visiting this link: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/divaniazzahra/mental-health-dataset/data. It consists of 17 columns with over 290,000 rows.

Based on the dataset description on Kaggle, the data was gathered through a global survey during a specific time period with the intention to track mental health trends of people all over the world with various backgrounds.

Step 1: Cleaning data¶

First, I will import various Python libraries that will be used to perform data cleaning, data visualization, and finally, data analysis. I'll also need to clean the data in case there are null values and I would need to change text string data into numbers (encoding the data).

Since timestamps are unique to each survey submission, I will drop the column because it does not provide information on behavioral responses. But I am curious about how much of the data was gathered in certain years, so I will extract the year before removing the column.

Step 3: Analyzing data¶

Now that our data has been converted into numbers, we can now plot them on a graph. Let's look at a correlation heatmap to see how all the variables relate to each other.

The correlation heatmap reveals that there are some factors that have a higher correlation coefficient compared to others. For example, treatment and family history have a positive correlation coefficient of 0.37. We also see which features we can potentially drop based off the correlation heatmap because it has a coefficient of 0, meaning there is no correlation at all.

Although there are some correlation values near 0, I will still analyze each feature and their relevance to my goal. I'll use subplots for every 3 features to help us see the distributions between treatment and all the other features in the dataset. Let's look at the work-related features first.

In [22]:
plt.figure(figsize = (18, 5))
plt.subplots_adjust(hspace = 0.3, wspace = 0.5)

    plt.xticks(rotation = 30)
    plt.ylabel("frequency")

Occupation: I do not think that the occupation feature would be helpful in the clustering model because no matter what job title you have, anyone can expereince mental health issues, so I'll drop this column. However, after we train the model, it may be helpful to see how symptoms differ between each job.

Self employed: This feature represents the distribution of respondents that are self-employed or not self-employed and their decision to seek treatment. I don't think that being self-employed is something that can affect behavioral patterns, so I will also drop this column.

Work interest: Unlike the other features, I do think that work interest can affect a person's mental health because their level of motivation can definitely influence behavioral patterns, so I'll keep this feature. For example, if a student isn't motivated because of internal (self-doubt, depression, etc.) or external (low grades, too much work, etc.) factors, they may exhibit behaviors like turning in assignments late.

In [23]:
plt.figure(figsize = (18, 5))

behavioral_features = ['days_indoors', 'changes_habits', 'coping_struggles']

    plt.subplot(1, 3, i + 1)
    sns.countplot(data = mh, x = feature, hue = 'treatment', palette = 'deep')
    plt.title(f"Treatment vs. {feature}")
    plt.xticks(rotation = 30)
    plt.ylabel("frequency")

Days indoors: This feature represents the number of days respondents spend indoors. I do think that this feature can be a characteristic that influences mental health because it may reflect a respondent's motivation to spend time outside and it can also be a characteristic of social isolation. Although COVID did not happen when this survey was taken, it is a good example of how staying indoors affected people's mental health. During quarantine, people were required to stay inside, so it was hard to interact with other people and it took a toll on their mental health as a result. Therefore, I will keep this feature in the dataset.

Changes habits: This feature represents whether a respondent has experienced changes in habit. I think it could help indicate if someone is going through mental health problems because it may indicate that they are changing habits to adapt or cope with their struggles, so I'll keep this feature too. Since I'll be basing my clusters off of treatment, this feature is relevant to behavioral patterns because cognitive behavioral therapy is a type of treatment that addresses various types of behavior.

Coping struggles: This feature is basically the generalized version of the changes in habit feature. I do think it's worth keeping this feature in the dataset because it is a behavioral response that indicates how people deal with their struggles. If a respondent has a hard time dealing with their issues, it can influence them to seek treatment to deal with it in a more effective way.

In [24]:
plt.figure(figsize = (18, 5))

Family history: This feature represents whether a respondent's family has a history of mental health disorders. I think it could help indicate mental health issues because genetics can play a role in mental health disorders, so it is important to keep this feature in the data.

Mental health history: This column is about whether or not the respondent has a mental health history. If they do, there is a chance their behavior patterns may recur which can aid the clustering model into determining what kind of behaviors can indicate that someone is struggling. Therefore, I think this is also an important feature to keep in the dataset.

Mental health interview: I do not think that going through a mental health interview contributes much to a respondent's behavioral response to mental health issues. Whether someone goes through with a mental health interview or not does not seem to greatly affect their choice to seek treatment. There is also a chance the respondent does not feel the need to be interviewed about their mental health because they're already aware of their issues, so I will drop this feature.

In [25]:

Mood swings and growing stress: These features represent whether respondents have been experiencing mood swings or an increase in stress. I do think that these features go hand in hand because if we refer back to the correlation heatmap, there is a negative correlation between these 2 variables (more stress means more mood swings and vice versa). This is because stress can affect the way people behave towards something, but sometimes these mood swings are not caused by stress, so I think this is another feature worth keeping in the dataset.

Care options: I think this feature would help with the clustering model because the availability of care options can definitely influence whether a respondent decides to seek treatment for their mental health problems or not. The graph shows us that respondents are more likely to seek help if they can utilize any available resources, and vice versa if they can't, but this is not the case for others. So, I'll keep this feature too.

Social weakness: This feature represents the respondent's difficulty with social aspects of life such as interactions or developing/maintaining relationships. Socializing is such an important part of personal growth and provides a sense of belonging and safety, so I think this is an important feature to keep in the dataset. It would also be beneficial to see how much social weakness can affect behavioral responses.

Now, we can finally drop the features we determined to be unnecessary and start training the model.

Step 4: Training data¶

Now that our data is ready, we will train the K-Means clustering model. Before we fit our data into the clustering model, we need to know how many clusters is optimal for our dataset. The elbow curve can be used to help us find the ideal number of clusters for the model which will be represented by the variable k.

In [27]:
# calculating the right k value
wcss = []
for i in range(1, 11):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters = i, init = 'k-means++', n_init = 'auto') 
    kmeans.fit(mh2)
    wcss.append(kmeans.inertia_)
fig = plt.figure(figsize = (3, 3))
plt.grid(alpha = 0.3)
plt.plot(np.arange(1, 11), wcss)
plt.title('Elbow Curve')
plt.show()

Our curve reveals a bent point when k = 4. That means we'll specify the number of clusters to be 4 in the function parameters.

In [28]:
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters = 4, init = 'k-means++', n_init = 'auto')
kmeans.fit(mh2)
y_kmeans = kmeans.predict(mh2)

cluster_df = pd.DataFrame()

After training the data, I've mapped each row of the dataframe to their respective cluster. We can use the indexes to find which rows make up each cluster in the original dataframe. This block of code made dataframes for each cluster so I could see how large each cluster is and to further confirm that there are 4 clusters.

In [52]:
# filters rows where treatment is yes and where treatment is no
# this makes it easier to read the output of each cluster instead of using a for loop

def filter_treatment_cluster(cluster_df, mh, number):
    index = cluster_df[cluster_df['cluster'] == number].data_index.values
    print(f"Cluster {number}:")
    
    treatment_yes = mh.loc[index][mh.loc[index]['treatment'] == "Yes"]
    treatment_no = mh.loc[index][mh.loc[index]['treatment'] == "No"]
    
    display(treatment_yes)
    display(treatment_no)
    print()

Cluster 0 Analysis:¶
This cluster consists of respondents who are housewives or work in business. When comparing the columns of each group, both occupations share similarities in treatment and non-treatment groups such as:


    

  • Not being self employed
    • 

  • Spending 15-30 days indoors
    • 

  • No mental health history
    • 

  • Low mood swings
    • 

  • Coping struggles
    • 

  • No work interest
    • 

  • Potential social weakness
    • 

  • (Mostly) no mental health interview
    • 



However, there are some notable differences in both groups such as:


    

  • Family history for mental health
    • 

  • Availability of care options
    • 



I do think it's important to note the mixed responses between housewives and business respondents for both groups in these categories:


    

  • Growing stress
      

    • Housewives experienced an increased level of stress.
      • 

    • Business respondents did not have increased stress.
      • 

    

    • 

  • Changes in habit
      

    • Housewives experienced changes in habit.
      • 

    • Business respondents may have experienced changes in habit, but are not too sure if they have or not.
      •

This cluster consists of respondents who work in business or as a student. When comparing the columns of each group, I noticed no matter whether the respondents have received treatment or not, they mostly shared similarities such as:


    

  • Not being self employed
    • 

  • Growing stress
    • 

  • Potential changes in habit
    • 

  • No mental health history
    • 

  • A mix between no or existing coping struggles
    • 

  • (Potential) interest in work
    • 

  • Potential social weakness
    • 

  • (Mostly) no mental health interview
    • 



Like the previous cluster, there are differences between the groups such as:


    

  • Family history for mental health
    • 

  • Availability of care options
    •

Step 5: Conclusion¶
Main differences:¶
Each cluster had their own shared set of symptoms, but I believe that the family history and care option features are factors that had the most impant on a respondents' decision to get treatment as these differences were present in all clusters. If we look back at the correlation heatmap, the family history and care option features that had a significantly higher correlation coefficient (0.371 and 0.291 respectively) compared to all the other features in the dataset.


Generally, respondents who have a family history of mental health disorders is a characteristic that puts the respondent at risk for developing the same or similar mental health disorders as someone in their family tree, and were found in the treatment group. Respondents without a family history were found in the non-treatment group.


Additionally, the availability of care options is another factor that influences a respondent's decision to get treatment or not. In general, respondents who were aware of care options got treatment and respondents who weren't aware of care options didn't get treatment, though in both groups there were some respondents that weren't sure or don't know about care options.


Symptoms between different occupations:¶
If you recall the columns we dropped (self employment, mental health interview) before training the data, they will not be considered as a symptom when we talk about each occupation. Factors that don't negatively affect a respondent's wellbeing will also not be included as a symptom (i.e no increase in stress levels, no mental health history).


Based on our findings, respondents that seek treatment with these jobs may have the following symptoms that indicate that they are struggling from mental health issues:
